               <head>To the Reader.</head>
               <p>
                  <lb/>
                  <lb/>
THat (gentle Reader) which<lb/>
at the earnest request of<lb/>
<normalised orig="certaine" auto="true">certain</normalised> my good friends, I<lb/>
refused to do (as <normalised orig="diuers" auto="true">divers</normalised> can<lb/>
<normalised orig="testifie" auto="true">testify</normalised>) <normalised orig="necessitie" auto="true">necessity</normalised> now <normalised orig="forceth" auto="true">forces</normalised><lb/>
me <normalised orig="vnto" auto="true">unto</normalised>: namely, to<lb/>
publish this my Sermon in<lb/>
print, which at the appointment<lb/>
of the <normalised orig="reuerend" auto="true">reverend</normalised> father in God, my Lord the<lb/>
Bishop of London, I made at <normalised orig="Paules" auto="true">Paul's</normalised> <normalised orig="Crosse" auto="true">Cross</normalised> on the 25.<lb/>
day of <normalised orig="Iune" auto="true">June</normalised> last past: the which in words I <normalised orig="haue" auto="true">have</normalised> very<lb/>
little altered, so far as my notes and <normalised orig="memorie" auto="true">memory</normalised> would<lb/>
<normalised orig="serue" auto="true">serve</normalised> me, but in matter and substance nothing at all,<lb/>
as they which then heard me may easily <normalised orig="perceiue" auto="true">perceive</normalised>. One<lb/>
place I <normalised orig="haue" auto="true">have</normalised> by occasion <normalised orig="somwhat" auto="true">somewhat</normalised> <normalised orig="inlarged" auto="true">enlarged</normalised>, the reason<lb/>
whereof is <normalised orig="rendred" auto="true">rendered</normalised> in the margent. Now <normalised orig="heerin" auto="true">herein</normalised>, specially<lb/>
in the former part, handling matters of most <lb/>
great <normalised orig="controuersie" auto="true">controversy</normalised> between the Papists and <normalised orig="vs" auto="true">us</normalised>, which<lb/>
<normalised orig="altogither" auto="true">altogether</normalised> would <normalised orig="seeme" auto="true">seem</normalised> to rely <normalised orig="vpon" auto="true">upon</normalised> the Doctors, I<lb/>
<normalised orig="vsed" auto="true">used</normalised> <normalised orig="diuers" auto="true">divers</normalised> authorities of <normalised orig="som" auto="true">some</normalised> of the ancient fathers,<lb/>
chiefly of that most excellent Doctor S. Augustine: <lb/>
the causes whereof I briefly <normalised orig="rendred" auto="true">rendered</normalised> in the Sermon it<lb/>
<normalised orig="selfe" auto="true">self</normalised> (as it is to be <normalised orig="seene" auto="true">seen</normalised>) which I thought would <normalised orig="haue" auto="true">have</normalised><lb/>
satisfied the reasonable hearer. <normalised orig="Notwitstanding" auto="true">Notwithstanding</normalised>, one,<lb/>
whom I <normalised orig="neuer" auto="true">never</normalised> heard of before that time (and what he<lb/>
is God <normalised orig="knoweth" auto="true">knows</normalised>) shortly after in the same place (as it<lb/>
was reported to me) did bitterly <normalised orig="reproue" auto="true">reprove</normalised> me for so doing.<lb/>
Whether he <normalised orig="hath" auto="true">has</normalised> in this point, <normalised orig="vnaduisedly" auto="true">unadvisedly</normalised>, and<lb/>
<normalised orig="vncharitably" auto="true">uncharitably</normalised> abused me or not, let it be <normalised orig="iudged" auto="true">judged</normalised> by the<lb/>
reading of the very same things, in the same order<lb/>
that they were then <normalised orig="vttered" auto="true">uttered</normalised>. The <normalised orig="iudgement" auto="true">judgment</normalised> whereof<lb/>
I refer to all the godly learned and discreet readers.<lb/>
                  <lb/>
                  <fw type="pageNum">A 2</fw>
                  <pb n="1"/>
                  <lb/>
For my part, I take God to <normalised orig="witnes" auto="true">witness</normalised>, who is the searcher<lb/>
of all <normalised orig="mens" auto="true">men's</normalised> harts, that I <normalised orig="tooke" auto="true">took</normalised> this <normalised orig="busines" auto="true">business</normalised> in<lb/>
hand, in the <normalised orig="feare" auto="true">fear</normalised> of God, directing my whole Sermon<lb/>
to these ends principally, that our faith might <normalised orig="bee" auto="true">be</normalised><lb/>
grounded <normalised orig="vpon" auto="true">upon</normalised> the <normalised orig="onely" auto="true">only</normalised> truth of Gods word: that<lb/>
false <normalised orig="counterfet" auto="true">counterfeit</normalised> religion might be detected an abhorred:<lb/>
that all worldly confidence and <normalised orig="wickednes" auto="true">wickedness</normalised><lb/>
might be <normalised orig="auoided" auto="true">avoided</normalised>: and that true Christian peace possessing<lb/>
our harts and our minds, we might <normalised orig="knowe" auto="true">know</normalised> and<lb/>
<normalised orig="performe" auto="true">perform</normalised> our <normalised orig="dutie" auto="true">duty</normalised> towards God and our Prince, and<lb/>
also one towards another in this present life, that <normalised orig="heerafter" auto="false">hereafter</normalised><lb/>
we may <normalised orig="enioy" auto="true">enjoy</normalised> <normalised orig="euerlasting" auto="true">everlasting</normalised> life.<lb/>
In the <normalised orig="meane" auto="true">mean</normalised> time, let <normalised orig="vs" auto="true">us</normalised> take diligent heed, to<lb/>
the <normalised orig="counsell" auto="true">counsel</normalised> and <normalised orig="commandement" auto="true">commandment</normalised> of the blessed Apostle<lb/>
to the Philippians, who <normalised orig="biddeth" auto="true">bids</normalised> that nothing be <lb/>
done through contention, or <normalised orig="vaine" auto="true">vain</normalised> <normalised orig="glorie" auto="true">glory</normalised>, but that in <lb/>
<normalised orig="meeknes" auto="true">meekness</normalised> of mind, <normalised orig="euery" auto="true">every</normalised> man esteem other better than<lb/>
<normalised orig="himselfe" auto="true">himself</normalised>. <normalised orig="Looke" auto="true">Look</normalised> not (saith he) <normalised orig="euery" auto="true">every</normalised> man on his <normalised orig="owne" auto="true">own</normalised><lb/>
things, but <normalised orig="euery" auto="true">every</normalised> man also on the things of other men.<lb/>
Then <normalised orig="followeth" auto="true">follows</normalised> immediately in the same place, the<lb/>
most <normalised orig="woonderfull" auto="true">wonderful</normalised> example of our <normalised orig="Sauior" auto="true">Saviour</normalised>, who for our<lb/>
sakes humbled <normalised orig="himselfe" auto="true">himself</normalised> to the lowest degree, that we<lb/>
in <normalised orig="humilitie" auto="true">humility</normalised> following his most blessed example, may<lb/>
by him and with him in the end be exalted.<lb/>
Whereunto, that we may effectually <normalised orig="conforme" auto="true">conform</normalised> our<lb/>
<normalised orig="selues" auto="true">selves</normalised>, I will conclude with the same <normalised orig="praier" auto="true">prayer</normalised>, that the <lb/>
Aspostle <normalised orig="vseth" auto="true">uses</normalised>, writing to the Romans: <quote type="biblical" ana="Rom 15.5">The God of<lb/>
    patience and consolation</quote>, <normalised orig="giue" auto="true">give</normalised> <normalised orig="vs" auto="true">us</normalised>, that we <quote type="biblical" ana="Rom 15.5">be like minded<lb/>
    one towards another, according to Christ <normalised orig="Iesus" auto="true">Jesus</normalised></quote>,<lb/>
that we <quote type="biblical" ana="Rom 15.6">with one mind, and with one mouth, may praise<lb/>
    God <normalised orig="euen" auto="true">even</normalised> the father of our Lord <normalised orig="Iesus" auto="true">Jesus</normalised> Christ</quote>, Amen.<lb/>
                  <lb/>
Thine in the Lord <normalised orig="Iesus" auto="true">Jesus</normalised>,<lb/>
WILLIAM GRAVET.<lb/>
               </p>
